Who We Are:
We are a premier academic and arts focused school. By combining rigorous academic programming with pre-professional training in the performing, visual and media arts, we inspire our students' creativity and thought, while providing an essential educational foundation that appeals to any university. We offer programs in dance, film, music, stage design, audio production, songwriting, theatre, and visual arts. Our alumni may be found at top professional venues and universities around the world. 
Our Programs:
Why: Art is a way of thinking; the mental agility to think different and not be afraid to experiment. Thus we engage and cultivate the creative mind while laying a foundation for a lifelong love of learning and success.

How: We provide a holistic and dynamic educational curriculum. Our students spend their days immersed in both academics and art. They're building their skills to become creative thinkers in any discipline with a perseverance to curiosity and new ideas. Through a constant cycle of collaboration, work ethic, self-discipline, fortitude, and grit, students are more agile for any university program or artistic endeavor. 

** This document is a living document - one that is adjusted and shifted based on constant communication and feedback from all stakeholders. Public forums include:
Monthly Parents/Principal meetings 
Booster Club Meetings
Community Council Meetings
Board Meetings
Individual Parent/Community/Student Meetings

Staff/Parent/Student Compact & Expectations:

THSA students will:
Provide high-quality, research-based instruction
Strive for students to engage in their best work
Set high expectations for all work and programming
Communicate effectively
Create a culture of family
Differentiate work for individual student needs
Seek for truth in all endeavors through feedback
Engage in school communication weekly
Understand classroom and program expectations
Support students and school through ride-sharing, food and activities/ programs
Provide feedback

Engage in the educational and arts environment each day

Be a part of the Tuacahn Family

Create:
We create meaningful work using curiosity and a passion for lifelong learning.
We collaborate often and iterate work multiple times prior to final turn in date.
We are engaged in the learning process; understanding all the requirements associated with success.
Advance:
We are prepared for class, and turn in assignments/work when due. We own our learning.
We respect the time of peers, faculty and learning.
We will engage in rigorous curriculums offered by the school to push thinking and ability.
Premier:
We work hard in all endeavors: hard work beats talent until talent decides to work hard.
We believe innovation is an attitude. We fail fast and often to get better.
We hold ourselves and others to a higher level - we all deserve that respect.
Truth:
We believe candid feedback is essential to learning.
We adjust and pivot to feedback given, understanding that it is to make us better.
We are honest in our work - ensuring that what we do and turn in is original. 
Family:
We work hard to empower all students to connect their passion.
We cultivate a broader perspective of the world to promote diversity and unity.
We are inspired by our home and take care of it together.

 *Review all student policies including but not limited to: discipline, SPED, 504, bullying, etc., on the school website and in the Parent – Student Handbook
 
DRESS CODE: 
Students should be in appropriate and approved dress code at all times, regardless of class/activity.

EXPECTATIONS: 
All pants/shorts/leggings/joggers/jeans will be solid black with NO mesh inserts, lines, rips, tears, white/color stitching, etc.
Shorts and skirts must be at fingertip length when standing (for quick reference checks). 
Outside logos on outerwear must not be greater than 2”.
All shirts will be official THSA gear purchased through the school. 
We offer a variety of t-shirts and many shows/clubs sell shirts throughout the year. 
We offer a variety of outerwear if students are generally cold inside - approved inside and in class.
A personal winter coat is allowed from Nov-Feb, but should not be worn inside the classroom. 
Sadies sweatshirts and t-shirts are NOT part of dress code and should not be worn during the school day.
Long sleeve shirts CAN be worn underneath THSA t-shirts (if appropriate). 
Only official THSA hats/beanies are allowed. 

Discipline Procedure for dress code violations:
1st Offense: Student is caught or reported out of dress code – student will be asked to change or “fix” the issue – if student is not able to change, student will be in ISS for the remainder of the day.
2nd Offense: Student will be asked to fix issue, Dean of Students (DoS) will document and make contact to parent – if student is not able to change, student will be in ISS for the remainder of the day (level 100 discipline). 
3rd Offense: Student will be in ISS for a full day (level 100 discipline). DoS will log entry and contact parent. 
4+ Offense: Student will be in ISS or OSS for a full day (level 200 discipline). Student may be removed from performance group/activities for current or future quarters. DoS will log entry and contact parent. 

ELECTRONIC DEVICES: 
Cell phones, and all electronic devices, should NOT be out in any class unless a teacher specifically asks students to use them during a period of time. If you need to get a hold of your student, please call Heather in the main office at 435.652.3201.

Any student using social media accounts or media of any kind using the Tuacahn names, images, names of employees, or students in an inappropriate, slanderous or defaming manner will receive a minimum Level 300 discipline, resulting in at least 3 days Out of School Suspension.

ATTENDANCE:
TARDIES: In a school for the performing arts, students are expected to be in attendance, and have the understanding that being a part of our school is a privilege. Excessive tardies may result in a deduction in a student’s grade(s), due to missing classroom collaborative work/assignments. A tardy is defined as reporting to class after the class has started. A student arriving more than 15 minutes after a class has started is considered absent. Students who are tardy not only disrupt the learning process for their peers and teacher by walking in late, but also forfeit learning opportunities for themselves. 

Total Tardies (per quarter/ per class) will result in the following: 
3 tardies: Dean of Students (DoS) pulls daily report and emails parent/guardian for students who have gotten 2 tardies in an individual class.
4 tardies: Dean of Students calls home. Log entry by DoS, and assigns Student in jeopardy of being dismissed from audition class/club for the next quarter (level 100 discipline).
6 + tardies: DoS contacts the parent(s) and student for a conference. In school suspension or other interventions as per necessary (level 200/300 discipline). Student may be dismissed from auditioned class for current or future quarters.

ABSENCES: Students may have a maximum of 3 excused absences, per class, per quarter, and 12 per year, prior to any disciplinary action taking place. This is a 93% attendance rate. Being at school is important to achieve and be part of the school community. Choosing to be absent may affect participation in extracurricular activities and auditioned classes. 

Absences may be considered excused for the following reasons: illness, family emergency, funeral, legal matters, and religious holiday. If a student will be out of school for three (3) or more days due to illness, the student MUST provide a note from a doctor or nurse specifying the amount of time excused.

If a student is absent from school for ten (10) consecutive school days or more, and the student’s parent or guardian has not contacted the school with an explanation for the absences with official documentation, or otherwise, expressing their intent to have their student attend the school, the student will be deemed to have voluntarily dropped from school enrollment.

Absences will likely affect a student’s grade in the classroom, as they will miss in-class assignments and group work that will not be able to be made up individually. Classroom policy of absences coinciding with failing grades are as follows: 
All absences are per class, per quarter, not total absences, and all absences are considered in the total, excused and unexcused.
At 4 absences per class - first email sent to parents from teacher.
At 6 absences per class - second email to guardian cc: Dean of Students (DoS) or counselor will contact parents and discuss the concern and possible solutions.
At 8 absences per class, contact to guardian, student/guardian are required to meet with administration/counselors to discuss solutions/alternative placements.
At 10+ absences students/guardian may be required to meet with an administrator to determine court referral as per administration - student may be referred to juvenile court or youth court for excessive attendance/ truancies.
At 15+ absences and with a failing grade, student will fail the class and be transferred to an online version of that class immediately to recover the credit, students will have to pay the fee for credit recovery (per quarter).
If a student recovers the credit it will replace the credit for graduation, but not on the transcript as per state policy.
Discipline as defined by DoS or administration following the Parent-Student Handbook.

GRADING:
THSA will provide personalized, collaboratively designed work, that is authentic and equitable. Teaching will support student motivation to learn, take risks, and succeed. Homework will be assigned in every class as appropriate – designed to enhance learning or provide practice. Students will receive a minimum of 1 graded assignment per week (9 per quarter). 

A 100-90%
Advanced Mastery
B 89-80%
Proficient Mastery
C 79-70%
Developing Mastery
D 69-60%
Beginning Mastery
F/I 59-0%
No Mastery / Missing
Submitted Work
Work that is submitted past its due date is given a graded score and a reduction of 25% as the goal is for students to achieve mastery of content; part of college preparation is understanding due dates and managing time. Teachers have the right to refuse work that is not done to expectation or any regard to mastery. Work that is refused will not be counted as on-time, but rather late with the 25% deduction. Students should take pride in their work and submit the best possible reflection of mastery and growth at the due date. 
Work that has already been turned in and graded, can be resubmitted to show growth and mastery of work at any time in the quarter, to receive a higher grade – up to 89%.
If a student turns in an assignment late from the original due date, the grade cannot be increased above a 75%.
Assignments that are copied, plagiarized or otherwise not original work (whether fully or partially), will receive an “F” grade (0), and student(s) will not have the opportunity to make the assignment up. 

Assessment Policies
All projects and assignments will be assessed throughout the scope of the work (formative assessment), to ensure that work is being completed on time and at a mastery level. These can be classroom assignments, group conversations, presentations, homework, small projects, essays, etc. See submitted work for resubmission policy. 
Summative assessments are tests, exams or major projects (groups or individuals). These assessments are given at the end of a lesson, unit, quarter or semester to determine mastery of content. DOCS_modelChunk = [{"ty":"is","ibi":12427,"s":"Honors credit can be provided to any students who have provided advanced mastery and completed extended learning opportunities (Honors work should not be “more work throughout the course (i.e. more problems), but rather, work that correlates with the content and other relevant sources that pushes thinking).

PERFORMANCE ELIGIBILITY/ CODE OF CONDUCT:
Student Performer Code of Conduct (a separate form must be filled out to participate as a THSA performer)
It is an honor to participate in the proud tradition of performance at Tuacahn High School for the Arts. I recognize that THSA expects me to experience personal growth, academic achievement, and performance success. I appreciate that membership on a THSA Company is a privilege, not a right.

I acknowledge that, as a THSA student-performer, I also have significant responsibilities. I recognize that I am among the most visible students on campus and in the wider community, and that I am expected to behave as a respectful member of the THSA family and in a manner that is consistent with its values. Because THSA student-performers are held to high standards of conduct, I understand the need to exercise good judgment and conduct myself with honesty, integrity, and respect for others at all times.



Auditioned Companies - (Classes/After School) 
Students in auditioned classes (PAC, Dance Company, Yearbook, Choir, Leadership, Sound Prod II, Art Prod, Master Prod, 3-D Design, Ballroom, and Guitar Ensemble) or any after school group (Theatre Company, Shakespeare Company, and Improv Company), should understand that they are ambassadors of the school, both through performance and academics.
The student shall maintain a C average (2.0) and will be checked by the instructor each quarter. Failure to maintain this standard will result in the student being removed from the company until the next check-point. 
Students will remain in good standing with all academic or behavioral expectations (located in the Student-Performer Code of Conduct and the Parent/Student Handbook) quarter to quarter, year to year. Students must not receive a level 200, 300, 400, or 500 discipline demerit, which includes repeated violations of level 100. Example: The “slate” is not clean at the end of the school year. If a student has discipline policy violations or a sub 2.0 GPA in Q4 of the current year, this will affect their performance group standing in Q1 of the following year. Students who are ineligible to perform for any reason cannot be enrolled in a performance/audition class during the time of their ineligibility.

COMMUNICATION POLICY:
Our main source of communication with parents and students is through PowerSchool, with grading, attendance, tardies, and discipline. It is the responsibility of the student and parent/guardian to ensure that they have access to this tool. Teachers will use PowerSchool to email parents and communicate attendance as well as academic performance. Other sources of school event information are: website, weekly email blasts, and our Instagram account (@thsa_official)

If there are any question(s) regarding a specific class, grade, tardy, attendance, assignment, placement, part, etc., please follow the process below. It is designed to give students the opportunity to advocate for themselves, all while having parental and school support. Steps should not be skipped, and student(s) should be involved and present in all aspects, unless it is not appropriate:
Step 1: Student should reach out to teacher to resolve any concern
Step 2: Parent + student should schedule a time to talk with teacher (phone/in-person)
Step 3: Parent + student should reach out to Dean of Students and teacher
Step 4: Parent + student should reach out to Principal for a meeting
Step 5: Principal will meet with all parties involved for an appropriate resolution
Step 6: Parent can appeal the Principal’s decision to the School Board

In order to qualify for the classes, you must complete an entire year and receive an “B” grade with no more than 3 excused absences and/or tardies per quarter. In addition, students must engage and be involved in high quality collaborative design, candid feedback and original work. Additionally, students must not receive a level 200, 300, 400, or 500 discipline demerit, which includes repeated violations of level 100. Students must also participate in all required performances/events. 

For a Theatre Company letter, a student must have a significant role in a minimum of two theatrical productions over the course of the year. Ensemble members do not qualify for a letter. 
In order to receive a letter in 3D design/Master Production/Audio Lab II, a student must qualify for all “class” expectations as well as contribute to 5+ school related pieces/performances. 
 


SPED/504/ADA:
We follow all policies and procedures, as applicable by state and federal government, for all Special Education, 504 or ADA needs for all students, faculty and staff. Please refer to the Student – Parent Handbook to understand all rights and responsibilities pertaining to this. 
 
FAMILY EXPECTATIONS/DISCIPLINE:
Parents and students should be aware of the parent/student discipline policy (outlined on the website and available in hard copy from the main office). This policy was created using national best practices and follows all federal, state, and local guidelines. It outlines behavioral family expectations and provides details for all disciplinary actions, using a progressive, student responsibility-centered, and solution based disciplinary model. 
The Dean of Students supports and works with students and teachers on behavioral expectations within the Tuacahn family. 
Students are expected to work on In School “Solutions” based outcomes with DoS, prior to In/Out School Suspension, if needed. (Based on nationally recognized programs and contributions by Larry Thompson from Responsibility-Centered Discipline and Brian Mendler, author of That One Kid.)
